<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99233298969356></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99233298969356><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99233298969356>RE: New Monk</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99233298969356#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=39551><span id=Guru>Osano</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>171 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jun 12th 4:03 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.24]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The argument about starting points has *always* been hot and heavy.&nbsp;&nbsp;There are decent arguments for dumping all your points into STR, AGI, or STA.  Even DEX has its supporters.<br><br>STR -- Better damage, a key Monk attribute.<br>AGI -- Better AC, a monk weakness.<br>STA -- Better HP, another monk weakness.<br>DEX -- Better skill-up rate, and better proc rate on weapons with effects.<br><br>Before giving my opinion, I'll tell you the bottom line:  It really doesn't matter all that much.  By picking and choosing your armor set, you can deal with just about any starting set of attributes.  Plus, the effect of 5 extra points here and there is really marginal.  The only one of the above which I think is a clear mistake is all DEX.<br><br>What I did:  Put 5 points in each.  Being brand new to EQ, but having played specialty fighter types for all my Roleplaying game life, I chose Monk (and very happy about that choice).  Not knowing any better, and not wanting to make any really HUGE mistakes, I just balanced it.  It turns out this is not a bad way to go.<br><br>Given hindsight, what I would have done:  Put 15 points into STA and 5 into STR.  Your HP bonus due to STA is increasingly large at higher levels. It can make a BIG difference.  When, as a lower level monk, I read posts recommending STA as the place to go, I thought that was stupid.  It's not.  Plus, it's the hardest stat to increase with equipment suitable for a monk.<br><br>There is a *lot* of AGI/DEX equipment for monks, so getting those up is really easy.  STR equipment is not so hard to come by either, but it's important to get it over 100, and the 5 extra points there helps.  That's why I make the recommendation that I do.<br><br>Is there anything wrong with +20 STR? Not at all, it's actually a highly recommended way to go.  Certainly no reason to ditch your monk, and better than +10 STR, +10 AGI in my opinion.  Just target AGI over STR for your equipment (very easy to do) and you'll be happy, I'm sure.<br><br>P.S. Forget EQ'lizer for monk advice.  www.monkly-business.com is awesome, but tends to be geared toward the higher end.  This is a great spot to post, with a number of regulars who like to answer questions, especially geared toward lower/mid levels.  You can take advice from people like Keyeluke or GLASS (especially for Iksar questions) and I hope myself with a good assurance of accuracy.<br>&nbsp;<br>Osano<br>Level 44 Human Monk<br>Tholuxe-Paells</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
