<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99235129880989></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99235129880989><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99235129880989>RE: New Monk</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99235129880989#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=35651><span id=Guru>Keyeluke</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>589 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jun 12th 9:08 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.30]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>This question is the one I researched most heavily before I started my monk.&nbsp;&nbsp;I put 10 into Agi, 5 Str, 3 Sta, 2 Dex.  Do I regret this choice?  No.  Do I think, in retrospect, that it was the best choice?  No. The worst choice?  No.<br><br>Will it make or break your monk?<br><br>No.<br><br>I did fine through my early and mid levels with the distribution I chose.  You'll do fine no matter how you distribute.  Each approach has its benefits and its proponents.  Osano covered the pros and cons very well.  My two cp worth of advice is to make an informed decision, then move on and don't worry about it any more.  Not only will your choices in gear have a greater effect on your character in the long run, but you'll see that there are more important things than stats.<br><br>At this stage of my life, the consensus seems to be that gear should be prioritized as follows:<br><br>1) AC First and Foremost (Never give up AC for stats)<br>2) Resists<br>3) HP<br>4) Stats<br><br>I had a lot of stat gear a while back.  I've slowly given up a decent amount of it in favor of AC gear.  Now my AC is good, my resists are getting better (nice to resist a 250 or 500 point DD every so often), and my stats are nothing special.  In a few more levels I'll be able to start doing the quests for the really good gear that gives both AC and stats, but for now my unbuffed stats are probably worse than those of many level 25-30 monks.  Doesn't really matter that much.  The buffs you will routinely get at higher levels will make how you distribute your 20 initial points pretty much irrelevant.  For example, a little while back I was fighting with a group in Dreadlands, and with buffs my str sta and agi were 150s or higher and my dex was 255.  You won't see these numbers for a while, but you WILL see stat buffs aplenty as you group, even at low levels.<br><br>If I had to do it again?  I'd probably go 10 Str 10 Sta.  Agi is overrated IMO, and you can get Agi gear AND Agi buffs very easily.  Dex is nice when training up your weapons skills and helping procs, but if you don't have a proc'ing weapon you don't seem to need it all that much other than at the beginning of each level.  Str helps your attack number directly, as well as your damage output.  Sta helps not only your HP, but will keep your endurance up during long melees (a real issue if you're swinging something even somewhat heavy).  I had the same reaction as Osano when I heard all STA - thought it was ludicrous.  I still wouldn't go all STA, but I see the merits of the argument clearly now.<br><br>Keyeluke <br>Monk of the Silent Fist, 45th Circle <br>Strange Brew <br>Druzzil Ro<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Keyeluke - <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415</a><br>Dripsy - <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=227922" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=227922</a></td></tr>
